k ThoughtThis staging of an elongated dialectical parallelism between Hegel’s classic text and major 19th-20th-century Black thinkers explodes the western canon of philosophy. Johnson and Mandela Gray show that Hegel’s abstract dialectic is transformed and critiqued when put into conversation with the lived dialectics of Black Thought: from Frederick Douglass and Harriet Jacobs through to Malcolm X and Angela Davis.While Hegel articulates the dynamic logics that we see in these Black thinkers, when they are placed in parallel and considered together, the whiteness, both explicit and implicit, of Hegelianism itself is revealed. Forcing Hegelianism into the embodied history of Black Thought reveals a phenomenology of America whose spirit is Black.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConsciousness. 0aPhenomenology. 0aPhilosophy, Black. 4aPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Movements / Phenomenology.2bisacsh1 aBaker, Ella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Anna Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglass, Frederick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDu Bois, W.E.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarvey, Marcus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHurston, Zora Neale, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Martin Luther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWashington, Booker T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWells, Ida B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel